<sect1 id="resources">
 <title>Further resources</title>
 <qandaset defaultlabel="qanda">
  <qandadiv>   
   <title>On your own machine</title>

   <qandaentry id="info-local"> 
    <question>
     <para>
       Where can I find information located on my machine?
     </para>
    </question>
    <answer>
     <para>
       Information is scattered all over the place. You can use the
       GNOME help browser (<command>gnome-help-browser</command> at
       the command line or select <menuchoice><guimenu>Programs</guimenu>
       <guimenuitem>Help system</guimenuitem></menuchoice> from the main
       GNOME menu) to browse most of these sources. A brief listing on a
       UNIX box would include the manual pages (<command>man gnome</command>),
       the info pages (<command>info gnome</command>), the documentation
       directory (usually <filename class="directory">/usr/doc/</filename>
       but it may be <filename class="directory">/usr/share/doc/</filename>
       on some systems) for packages, and the 
       <application>GNOME</application>-specific documentation for the
       GNOME help browser. You can also use your package management 
       tool as described earlier.
     </para>
    </answer>
   </qandaentry>
  </qandadiv>

  <qandadiv>
   <title>On the net</title>
   <para>
     The very first thing you need when trying to find resources on the
     net is a good search engine. Many of the archives mentioned below
     have search facilities. For general queries, an excellent search
     engine is <ulink type="http" url="http://www.google.com">Google</ulink>.
     Please please: before posting questions to lists, make at least a
     cursory effort to check that they have not been asked recently!
   </para>

   <qandaentry id="info-net"> 
    <question>
     <para>
       What about information on the net?
     </para>
    </question>
    <answer>

     <para>
       All over the place. A representative listing would include at
       least this lot below.
     </para>
     <para>
       The obvious place to start is the <ulink url="http://www.gnome.org"
       type="http">GNOME website</ulink>. Note that more detailed and
       technical information is at its sister site:
       <ulink type="http" url="http://developer.gnome.org">developer.gnome.org</ulink>.
     </para>
     <para>
       <ulink type="http" url="http://news.gnome.org/gnome-news/">Gnotices</ulink>
       is the website where much news is posted.
     </para> 
     <para>
       There are a variety of mailing lists for different purposes. A 
       reasonably complete mailing list page is at the <ulink type="http"
       url="http://www.gnome.org/resources/mailing-lists.html">main
       GNOME website</ulink>. Some lists are hosted elsewhere. Before
       going onto the complete (well, as far as I can make it) list,
       a caveat. Many are high-traffic. All of them prefer you make
       an attempt to check the archives before posting a question.
       Some search sites for specific lists are listed following the
       mailing lists themselves. 
     </para>
     <itemizedlist>
      <listitem>
       <para>
         <ulink type="http" url="http://www.eazel.com">Eazel</ulink> host
         <ulink 
         type="http" url="http://www.eazel.com/mailman/listinfo/">several 
         lists</ulink> of which the
         <ulink type="http" 
         url="http://www.eazel.com/mailman/listinfo/nautilus-list">Nautilus
         list</ulink> is a particularly useful one to know about.
       </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
       <para>
         <ulink type="http" url="http://www.helixcode.com">Helix Code</ulink>
         also host
         <ulink type="http"
         url="http://lists.helixcode.com/mailman/listinfo">several
         lists</ulink> of which the 
         <ulink type="http"
         url="http://lists.helixcode.com/mailman/listinfo/evolution">Evolution</ulink>
         list (for Evolution users) and the
         <ulink type="http"
         url="http://lists.helixcode.com/mailman/listinfo/beta">beta</ulink>
         (for people using the Helix GNOME distribution> are probably the
         most useful ones to know about. 
       </para>
      </listitem>
     </itemizedlist>
     <para>
      <note>
       <title>gnome-list and on-topicness</title>
       <para>
         The gnome-list mailing list in particular gets a lot of traffic,
         because people often aren't sure where to ask questions or simply
         don't know where to ask. It's really not the best place for
         X-related problems, distribution-related problems, questions on 
         how to mount a filesystem, perform backups, or what people's
         favourite mailers are.
       </para>
      </note>
     </para>
     <para>
        For non-GNOME or GNOME-and-particular distribution questions, 
        there are other mailing lists. Here's a partial list of where 
        to look:
     </para>
     <itemizedlist>
      <listitem>
       <para>
         Red Hat users can head for the redhat-list found at the
         <ulink type="http" url="http://www.redhat.com/mailing-lists/list_subscribe.html">Red
         Hat mailing lists</ulink> page on the
         <ulink type="http" url="http://www.redhat.com">Red Hat</ulink>
         website.
       </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
       <para>
         Debian users can head for several 
         <ulink type="http" url="http://www.debian.org/MailingLists/">Debian
         mailing lists</ulink> on the
         <ulink type="http" url="http://www.debian.org">Debian 
         website</ulink>.
       </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
       <para>
          Mandrake users can head for several
          <ulink type="http" url="http://www.linux-mandrake.com/en/flists.php3">Mandrake
          mailing lists</ulink> on the
          <ulink type="http" url="http://www.linux-mandrake.com/en/">Mandrake
          website</ulink>.
       </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
       <para>
         Caldera users can head for several
         <ulink type="http" url="http://www.caldera.com/support/forums/">Caldera
         mailing lists</ulink> on the 
         <ulink type="http" url="http://www.caldera.com">Caldera
         website</ulink>.
       </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
       <para>
         Slackware doesn't have a specific "general questions" mailing list 
         listed in its
         <ulink type="http" url="http://www.slackware.com/lists">mailing 
         lists</ulink> but there is apparently an active newsgroup which 
         handles a lot of newbie questions: alt.os.linux.slackware. 
       </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
       <para>
         FreeBSD users can head for several
         <ulink type="http" url="http://www.freebsd.org/handbook/eresources.html#ERESOURCES-MAIL">FreeBSD
         mailing lists</ulink> at the
         <ulink type="http" url="http://www.freebsd.org">FreeBSD website</ulink>.
         The best place for newbie questions is the freebsd-questions list.
         (Thanks to Andrew Mobbs for this.)
       </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
       <para>
         There are several new (as of June 2000)
         <ulink type="http" url="http://www.xfree86.org/mailman/listinfo">XFree86
         lists</ulink> at the 
         <ulink type="http" url="http://www.xfree86.org/">XFree86
         website</ulink>. The newbie list is described as being for
         general XFree86 setup and configuration problems. 
       </para>
      </listitem>         
     </itemizedlist>
     <para>
       Further contributions welcomed.
     </para>

     <para>
       Search engines for particular lists:
     </para>
     <itemizedlist>
      <listitem>
       <para>
         The <ulink type="http" url="http://www.google.com">Google</ulink>
         search engine appears to have indexed at least half of the 
         <ulink type="http" url="http://www.gnome.org">GNOME website</ulink>.
       </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
       <para>
         <ulink type="http" url="http://www.geocrawler.com">Geocrawler</ulink>
         has a
         <ulink type="http" 
         url="http://www.geocrawler.com/lists/3/Gnome/">searchable
         archive</ulink> of many GNOME-related mailing lists. It does
         not handle attachments very well, though.
       </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
       <para>
        <ulink type="http" url="http://www.somelist.com">Somelist</ulink>
        has an archive of 
        <ulink type="http"
        url="http://www.somelist.com/index.php3/167/">lots of GNOME 
        lists</ulink> which handles attachments.
       </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
       <para>
         Owen Taylor posted a 
         <ulink type="http"
         url="http://mail.gnome.org/pipermail/gnome-list/2000-August/041089.html">note</ulink>
         to gnome-list about some work on a searchable archive for the 
         gnome.org site. Currently it covers only a couple of the more
         technical lists. Follow the link for the URL. 
       </para>
      </listitem>
     </itemizedlist>

     <para>
       If you are looking for advice on a particular bug, it is well
       worth trying the various bug-trackers. Many people will include
       patches if they can. The most-used bug-trackers for GNOME are
       listed here. It is often useful to try lots of them: people put
       Helix bugs into Red Hat's tracker and Red Hat bugs into the
       main GNOME tracker and so on very commonly. 
     </para>

     <itemizedlist>
      <listitem>
       <para>
         The <ulink type="http" url="http://bugs.gnome.org">Wonderful GNOME 
         Bugtracker</ulink> is comprehensive, to put it mildly. 
       </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
       <para>
         The <ulink type="http" url="http://bugs.helixcode.com">Helix 
         Code bugtracker</ulink> is for Helix Code problems. 
       </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
       <para>
         Red Hat's <ulink type="http" url="http://bugzilla.redhat.com">Bugzilla</ulink>
         is not just for GNOME, but you can search under particular packages
         for GNOME problems and fixes.
       </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
       <para>
         Eazel's <ulink type="http" url="http://bugzilla.eazel.com">Bugzilla</ulink>
         may help if you are using Nautilus in particular.
       </para>
      </listitem>
     </itemizedlist>

     <para>
       The Users Guide can be a source of useful information: you can
       always find the latest version in your local mirror of
       <ulink type="ftp" 
       url="ftp://ftp.gnome.org/pub/GNOME/stable/sources/users-guide/">
       ftp.gnome.org/pub/GNOME/stable/sources/users-guide/</ulink>. It
       is available to browse online at
       <ulink type="http"
       url="http://www.labs.redhat.com/gug/users-guide/">
       http://www.labs.redhat.com/gug/users-guide/</ulink>.
     </para>
     <para>
       People who want to dig deeper may want to look at the
       <ulink type="http" url="http://cvs.gnome.org">CVS browser</ulink>
       which lets you see who's done what recently and what's currently
       in there. This is where all the central code for GNOME lives.
     </para>
     <para>
       Some applications are covered in more detail on other
       websites: the
       <ulink type="http" url="http://www.helixcode.com">Helix Code</ulink>, 
       <ulink type="http" url="http://www.eazel.com">Eazel</ulink> and
       <ulink type="http" url="http://www.labs.redhat.com/news.shtml">RHAD 
       Labs Rumor Mill</ulink>
       sites often have information; and many GNOME applications have
       homepages at the
       <ulink type="http" url="http://www.sourceforge.net">SourceForge</ulink>
       site: just search for the word <quote>gnome</quote> in the box.
     </para>
    </answer>
   </qandaentry>
  </qandadiv>
 </qandaset>
